            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-395-person2050">
                  SAMUEL 
                  BEAMAN
               <interp inst="t18260914-395-person2050" type="surname" value="BEAMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-395-person2050" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-395-person2050" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am carter to Samuel Cowley and Henry Hewetson. On the 15th of September I was bringing five bales of sheeting from Hoare's wharf to our warehouse, in Cateaton-street; I met the prisoner on the wharf, whom I had known some years - he had been a carter to Mr. Evans - he is now <rs id="t18260914-395-deflabel2216" type="occupation">patrol of St. Botolph, Aldgate</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-395-defend2047 t18260914-395-deflabel2216"></join>; we went to the <placeName id="t18260914-395-crimeloc2217">Coopers' Arms, public-house</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-395-crimeloc2217" type="placeName" value="Coopers' Arms, public-house"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-395-crimeloc2217" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-395-off2214 t18260914-395-crimeloc2217"></join>, to have some beer and my dinner - it was then between one and two o'clock; while I was at the house he went out and got my dinner - and as he went out, I saw through the window, that he put his hand on the rail of the waggon, and his foot on the wheel - but I did not see that he got into it, though he raised himself up; he returned in about five minutes, and after I had done my dinner, I drove away; when I got on to the Minories I missed a piece of sheeting-wrapper from my waggon; I think it might be five yards, or more; I had put it in, and the lock-chain over it. I had never said that previous to my going to the Cooper's Arms, he had seen me double it up, and put the lock-chain over it; he must have seen it when he raised himself up - he was near the cloth, and could get it; I went to his house that night - I found his wife at the gin-shop; I went with the officer and found the prisoner on his beat - he denied it to the officer - but when I went up to him, he said, if I went home with him, he would give it to me; I found it there.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did not the officer tell him he had stolen it? A. No; he said, "There has been a waggon robbed - do you know any thing about it?" I did not say. I would give him something to make an apron; I did not think any thing about his putting his hand and foot on the waggon. We drank the beer, and came up as far as Butcher-row, and had some rum; I did not ask the prisoner to hold the whip while I went up Morgan's-rents; I left the whip inside, and he brought it out, but I did not desire him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-395-person2051">
                  JAMES 
                  WITNEY
               <interp inst="t18260914-395-person2051" type="surname" value="WITNEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-395-person2051" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-395-person2051" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a headborough. I received information from the witness, at a quarter before ten o'clock, and went to the prisoner on his beat, in Nightingale-lane, with Beaman - I went up to the prisoner, and said, "Bates - you are charged with stealing a piece of linen out of a waggon to day;" he said he had not; I then stepped five or six yards back, and Beaman went up, and said."Bates"- I did not hear more, but when they had been in conversation about a minute Bates said, in a louder voice, "Yes, I did take it out of the waggon - if you come home with me you shall have it;" we all three went to his house, and, after searching a few minutes, we found this linen on the floor, at the foot of the stairs, in the lower room - the prisoner took it up. I took him to the watch-house.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. When you went up did not you charge him with stealing it? A. Yes - the carman knew what he was about - I think he was sober.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18260914-395-verdict2218" type="verdictDescription">
